## Unemployment {#unemployment}

The Hunter Valley's unemployment rate has continued to plunge since the highs reached in COVID. The 3-month moving average shows unemployment is now at 2.4% as of July 2023, down from 4.5% in July 2022. This figure is slightly less than the NSW-wide rate of 3.0% in July 2023, which has also only slightly declined in the last twelve months (down from 3.9%). The decline in the unemployment rate is partly driven by the increasing labour force participation rates over the period. That is, more people are seeking employment. The region's youth unemployment rate has also seen record lows, with the unemployment rate for July 2023 at 2.9%. This figure is now below the NSW-wide rate of 3.7%. Historically, a key challenge for policymakers is to achieve a low rate of unemployment without fuelling excessive increases in wages growth and inflation. Economists call the lowest rate of unemployment that achieves this the 'non-accelerating inflation rate of unemployment' or [NAIRU](https://www.rba.gov.au/speeches/2023/sp-dg-2023-06-20.html). Current estimates are that this rate is roughly 5% in Australia. These values are expressed with a 3-month moving average.

